{"id":"astro-ph/0403236","submitter":"Nicolas Pesenti","authors":"N. Pesenti, C. Dougados, S. Cabrit, J. Ferreira, F. Casse, P. Garcia,\n  D. O'Brien","title":"Predicted rotation signatures in MHD disc winds and comparison to DG Tau\n  observations","comments":"4 Pages, 4 Figures, to be published in A&A","journal-ref":"Astron.Astrophys. 416 (2004) L9","doi":"10.1051/0004-6361:20040033","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Motivated by the first detections of rotation signatures in the DG Tau jet\n(Bacciotti et al. 2002), we examine possible biases affecting the relation\nbetween detected rotation signatures and true azimuthal velocity for\nself-similar MHD disc winds, taking into account projection, convolution as\nwell as excitation gradients effects. We find that computed velocity shifts are\nsystematically smaller than the true underlying rotation curve. When outer\nslower streamlines dominate the emission, we predict observed shifts increasing\nwith transverse distance to the jet axis, opposite to the true rotation\nprofile. Determination of the full transverse rotation profile thus requires\nhigh angular resolution observations (< 5 AU) on an object with dominant inner\nfaster streamlines. Comparison of our predictions with HST/STIS observations of\nDG Tau clearly shows that self-similar, warm MHD disc wind models with lambda =\n13 and an outer radius of the disc ~ 3 AU are able to reproduce detected\nvelocity shifts, while cold disc wind models (lambda > 50) are ruled out for\nthe medium-velocity component in the DG Tau jet.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 10 Mar 2004 10:35:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-10"}
{"id":"astro-ph/0403237","submitter":"Giovanni Vladilo","authors":"Giovanni Vladilo","title":"The early build-up of dust in galaxies: A study of Damped Ly alpha\n  Systems","comments":"Accepted for publication on Astronomy & Astrophysics; 13 pages, 5\n  figures","journal-ref":"Astron.Astrophys. 421 (2004) 479-490","doi":"10.1051/0004-6361:20035897","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We present a study of the early build-up of dust in high redshift galaxies.\nThe study is based on the analysis of 38 Damped Ly alpha systems (DLAs) for\nwhich we derive the fraction of iron atoms in dust form, f_{Fe}. The sample is\nrepresentative of metal-poor galaxies in the redshift range 0.6 </= z </= 3.4\nselected on the basis of their absorption HI column density (N(HI) >/= 2 x\n10^{20} atoms cm^{-2}). We find that the dust fraction increases with\nmetallicity, from f_{Fe}~0 at [Fe/H] ~ -2 dex, up to f_{Fe} ~ 0.9 at solar\nmetallicity; the increase is fast below [Fe/H] ~ -1 dex and mild at higher\nmetallicities. We also find some evidence for an increase of f_{Fe} with cosmic\ntime; a large fraction of the systems younger than ~3 Gyr has f_{Fe} </~ 0.5.\nThese results indicate the dust-to-metal ratio increases in the course of\nchemical evolution, at variance with the hypothesis of an approximately\nconstant dust-to-metal ratio, commonly adopted in models of galactic evolution.\nThis hypothesis is consistent with local and high-redshift data only when the\nmetallicity is relatively high ([Fe/H] >/~ -1 dex). The results of this work\nsuggest that the main mechanisms of dust formation may be rather sensitive to\nthe level of metallicity attained by a galaxy in the course of its chemical\nevolution. A metallicity-dependent dust production by SNe II seems to be the\nmost promising mechanism for explaining the rise of f_{Fe} at [Fe/H] </~ -1\ndex.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 10 Mar 2004 10:46:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-10"}
